english:
  title: A Record of the Water-Crystal Society at Jiri Mountain
  author: Gwon Jeok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Humanity has long wandered in confusion. We have lost our original simplicity and chase endless desires, spending our entire lives adrift without finding our way out—such is the common plight of all. Yet there are those who regard wealth and status as refuse, who cast off fame and fortune like worn-out shoes. They delight in solitude and cherish quietude, their hearts turned to ash, their forms withered. They seek the path to liberation and say: "I need only save myself. How could I possibly save others?" This may be admirable for oneself, yet it falls short of greatness. But if one, moved by compassion for the world's suffering, seeks the path to liberation, and having found it for oneself, wishes to share it with all others, never resting until all are freed—such is the work of the great. Only such a one can accomplish both benefits without leaving their dwelling. This is why the Water-Crystal Society was established.

    The society's master bore the name Jin-eok, of the clan Lee. His father Seong served as Minister of Secretariat, and his mother, Lady Jeon, was the Princess Consort of Yonggung. From age eight he abstained from meat and blood; at eleven he took the monastic vow and studied under the Venerable Teacher Hye-deok at Hyeonhwa Temple. At twenty-six he excelled in the great examination. His learning and practice advanced daily, and all revered him. Yet by nature he scorned worldly affairs. Once, conversing with fellow monks like Hye-yak, he lamented: "Those who leave the home life seek only liberation. How can this be their true aim if they use it as a means for fame and profit?" From that moment he harbored the resolve to depart. He determined to establish a pure society in a sacred mountain, following the example of Donglin and Xihu. Yet finding the right place proved difficult. Hearing of an abandoned temple called Odae in Jiri Mountain, he investigated. For Jiri Mountain is the great sanctuary of our land—lofty and deep, vast and grand, without peer under heaven. Odae, situated on the mountain's southern face where five peaks rise and fall like layered terraces, took its name from this natural formation. A thousand peaks encircle and protect it; all valleys converge as one. The place seems a realm where immortals and sages dwell in hiding. Those who gaze upon it find their eyes dazzled and their hearts transported. The Great Illuminated National Master once traveled southward and came to this place. Wandering and surveying it, he declared: "Here is where the Great Dharma dwells." The master, hearing these words, went forth with courage and found his destination. He remained there and cleared the ground.

    The abbot of Haein Temple, Sangsung Ik-seung, and the superintendent of Gongbae Temple, Sangrok Young-seok, generously gave their private wealth to aid the endeavor. From princes and prime ministers down to worthy officials and esteemed monks of both contemplative and scholastic orders, and among the faithful laity, nearly three thousand wished to join. The monks Dam-ung and Ji-ung gathered donors; Soon-hyeon personally led craftsmen who wielded hammer and axe with urgent diligence. They raised eighty-six buildings. Halls and dormitories stood neat and ordered, inspiring visitors with visions of the Pure Land. The head monk Bop-yeon cast a statue of Amitabha Buddha; Sangsung Ik-seung erected a stone pagoda; Seonsa Young-seong installed woodblock sutras. Every necessity for living and every tool for practice, down to the smallest item, was provided. The aged found comfort and the ill found care. All assembled there dwelt in harmony and reverence, censuring fault and praising virtue, spurring one another on. Day and night they labored, together aspiring toward the Western Paradise.

    For those of exceptional wisdom and virtue who dwelt in the society, no fixed rules bound them. Whether reciting sutras, chanting the Buddha's name, or sitting in meditation, they were free to follow their inclination, allowing them to dwell at ease in natural realization. For all who joined the society, whether living or deceased, names were inscribed on wooden tablets. Twice monthly, according to the Scripture on Divining Karmic Retribution, lots were drawn and cast upon a wheel to divine the rewards of good and evil. The results were sorted into two boxes. Those who drew evil karmic fruit had the assembly perform confession on their behalf, then cast the wheel again until a good fruit appeared. Fearing that those who first drew good fruit might later fall into evil, the assembly cast the wheel once yearly for each member. Should one fall again, they performed confession anew, without end. Thus all who gathered like clouds might achieve liberation together, passing the ever-burning lamp into the boundless future. This is what is meant by accomplishing both benefits without departing one's hall.

    The master obtained a crystal and suspended it before the Amitabha statue to signify his luminous faith, and named the society thereby. Construction began in the seventh month of the fifth year of Xuanhe in the Song, in the year guimao, and was completed in the tenth month of the third year of Jianyan, in the year guiyou. They held dedication ceremonies for three days, inviting the head monk Seong-seon of Yomcheon Temple to expound the sutras. The emperor commanded Inspector Uin Eon-i to perform the incense offering, and thereupon granted two hundred silver pieces as a mark of favor. From that time, people from near and far turned their hearts in devotion, both monastic and lay, flocking to witness such flourishing transformation as had not been seen in recent ages.

    When the master saw that the society's work had been accomplished, he consulted with all the assembly and petitioned the throne to establish it as an eternal institution. From that time forward, those perfecting their virtue and dwelling in the society should take turns as society master, each serving a term of three years and succeeding one another without exception—thus ensuring its perpetuation. In the seventh year of Shaoxing, in the year dingsi, the master submitted a memorial stating: "Becoming a monk is not difficult; practicing the Way is difficult. But practicing the Way is not the hardest thing; encountering the right time is the hardest. We have been fortunate to be born in an age of peace and stability when the Great Way may flourish, allowing us to dwell at ease while cultivating pure practice. Long ago, when Huiyuan established his society, six hundred years passed before Shengchang arose. After Shengchang's society endured for one hundred and forty years, now the Water-Crystal Society has emerged. Thus is it rare to encounter one's time. Moreover, at Donglin, Liu Yimin composed the vow; at Xihu, Song Bai composed the monument inscription. Now, in establishing this society, its splendor rivals Donglin and Xihu across different ages with the same essence. If Your Majesty commands Confucian ministers to record its beginning and end, creating an imperishable transmission, this would be a worthy glory of the sage court."

    The emperor approved his request, bestowing a pagoda of pure gold and a thousand bushels of grain. He specially had his own calligraphy inscribed on the memorial stele—an unprecedented honor. He further sent an imperial envoy to install a Buddha's tooth relic, manifesting his reverence. He then commanded his servant Jeok to compose this record. I, being unworthy yet already enrolled as a society member, trembled at the command and found no words to decline. Therefore I merely record these dates and events.
  footnotes:
    - Donglin (東林) and Xihu (西湖) refer to famous Pure Land Buddhist societies established in China by Huiyuan and later by Shengchang, mentioned as models for this Korean society.
    - The Occupation Census Scripture (占察業報經) is a Buddhist text that describes divination methods for determining karmic consequences, which the society employs in their spiritual practice.
    - The 'two benefits' (二利) refer to the Buddhist concept of achieving both personal enlightenment and the liberation of all sentient beings—the core aim of the society.
    - Jiri Mountain (智異山) is one of Korea's sacred mountains, known for its spiritual significance and natural grandeur.
